description: {"blocks":[{"key":"8ul3q","text":"The assay I describe measures lactate concentration in a sample. The principle of the assay is to convert lactate in a sample and excess NAD+ in the buffer to pyruvate and NADH with lactic dehydrogenase. Pyruvate is trapped by hydrazine in the buffer to form pyruvate hydrazone, effectively decreasing concentrations of free pyruvate and driving forward lactate consumption. NADH can be observed on a microplate reader because it absorbs light at 340 nm. I adapted this assay for use in a microplate reader from \"A flexible system of enzymatic analysis\" by Oliver Lowry and Janet Passoneau (Lactate method II). It is reliable, inexpensive, and diagnostically useful for calculating cellular lactate production rates.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[{"style":"sup","offset":140,"length":1}],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"e7tqd","text":"Read absorbance at 340 nm or fluorescence (ex:340, em:460) to determine NADH levels in samples and standards. The reaction stops when absorbance or fluorescence no longer increases over time.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"9mvgd","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"9se0i","text":"Note:","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"4fhme","text":"Absorbance values approximately \u003e2 are normally outside the dynamic range of quantitation that you should trust. This may not work, in which case the next time you perform the assay, attempt a sample dilution series to determine the concentrations that lie within your standard curve and within the range of accurate quantitation by your spectrophotometer.","type":"unordered-list-item","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}
